{{Infobox scientist | name = Jack van Lint | image = Jack van Lint.jpg<!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = 220px | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1932|9|1|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Bandung]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2004|9|28|1932|9|1|df=y}} | death_place = | nationality = [[Netherlands|Dutch]] | fields = [[Mathematics]] | workplaces = [[Eindhoven University of Technology]] | alma_mater = [[Utrecht University]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Fred van der Blij]] | doctoral_students = | known_for = | awards = [[Euler Medal]] {{small|(1996)}} }}
'''Jacobus Hendricus ("Jack") van Lint''' (1 September 1932 – 28 September 2004) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] mathematician, [[professor]] at the [[Eindhoven University of Technology]], of which he was [[rector magnificus]] from 1991 till 1996.
He gained his Ph.D. from [[Utrecht University]] in 1957 under the supervision of [[Fred van der Blij]].<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=51426}}</ref> He was professor of mathematics at [[Eindhoven University of Technology]] from 1959 to 1997.
He was appointed a full professor at [[Eindhoven University of Technology]] at the age of 26 years. His field of research was initially [[number theory]], but he worked mainly in [[combinatorics]] and [[coding theory]].<ref>B. van Asch, A. Blokhuis, H. Hollmann, W. Kantor, H. van Tilborg, Jack van Lint (1932-2004): A survey of his scientific work, ''[[Journal of Combinatorial Theory]]'', Series A, 113 (2006), 1594-1613</ref>
Van Lint was honored with a great number of awards. He became a member of [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1972,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.dwc.knaw.nl/biografie/pmknaw/?pagetype=authorDetail&aId=PE00001629 |title=Jacob Hendricus van Lint (1932 - 2004) |language=Dutch |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> received four honorary doctorates, was an honorary member of the Royal Netherlands Mathematics Society (Koninklijk Wiskundig Genootschap), and received a [[Knighthood]].
==Books== * ''Coding Theory'', 1971. * [https://books.google.com/books/about/Combinatorial_Theory_Seminar_Eindhoven_U.html?id=IR96CwAAQBAJ ''Combinatorial Theory Seminar Eindhoven University of Technology''], 1974<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wilf, Herbert S.|authorlink=Herbert Wilf|title=Review of ''Algebraic graph theory'' by Norman Biggs and ''Combinatorial theory seminar'' by Jacobus H. van Lint|journal=Bull. Amer. Math. Soc.|year=1975|volume=81|issue=3|pages=536–538|url=http://www.ams.org/journals/bull/1975-81-03/S0002-9904-1975-13731-1/S0002-9904-1975-13731-1.pdf|doi=10.1090/s0002-9904-1975-13731-1}}</ref> * ''Introduction to Coding Theory'', Springer, Graduate Texts in Mathematics, 1982, 3rd. edition 1999. * with [[Peter Cameron (mathematician)|Peter Cameron]]: ''Designs, Graphs, Codes and their Links'', London Mathematical Society Lecture Notes, Cambridge University Press, 1980. * with [[Richard M. Wilson]]: ''A Course in Combinatorics'', Cambridge University Press, 1992. {{cite book|title=2nd edition|year=2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0uEgAwAAQBAJ}} * with [[Gerard van der Geer]]: ''Introduction to Coding theory and Algebraic Geometry'', Birkhäuser, 1988.
