{{Infobox molecular geometry | Image_File=seesaw-3D-balls.png | Symmetry_group= [[Cyclic symmetry in three dimensions|C<sub>2v</sub>]] | Atom_direction=4 | Bond_angle=90°, 90°<θ<120°, 180° | mu= >0| Examples= [[Sulfur tetrafluoride|SF<sub>4</sub>]]| }}
'''[[Disphenoid]]al''' or '''Seesaw''' is a type of [[molecular geometry]] where there are four bonds to a central atom with overall C<sub>2v</sub> [[symmetry group|symmetry]]. The name "seesaw" comes from the observation that it looks like a [[seesaw|playground seesaw]]. Most commonly, four bonds to a central atom result in [[Tetrahedral molecular geometry|tetrahedral]] or, less commonly, [[Square planar molecular geometry|square planar geometry]]. The seesaw geometry, just like its name, is unusual.
It occurs when a molecule has a [[steric number]] of 5, with the central atom being bonded to 4 other [[atom]]s and 1 [[lone pair]] (AX<sub>4</sub>E in [[VSEPR theory#AXE method|AXE notation]]). An atom bonded to 5 other atoms (and no lone pairs) forms a [[trigonal bipyramidal molecular geometry|trigonal bipyramid]]; but in this case one of the atoms is replaced by a lone pair. The atom replaced is always an equatorial atom, because the [[Lone pair|lone pairs]] repel other electrons more strongly than atoms do.
==Structure== Compounds with disphenoidal geometry (See-Saw Geometry) have two types of [[Ligand|ligands]]: axial and equatorial. The axial pair lie along a common bond axis so that are related by a bond angle of 180°. The equatorial pair of ligands is situated in a plane orthogonal to the axis of the axial pair. Typically the bond distance to the axial ligands is longer than to the equatorial ligands. The ideal angle between the axial ligands and the equatorial ligands is 90°; whereas the ideal angle between the two equatorial ligands themselves is 120°.
Disphenoidal molecules, like trigonal bipyramidal ones, are subject to [[Berry pseudorotation]]. Thus, the <sup>19</sup>F NMR spectrum of [[Sulfur tetrafluoride|SF<sub>4</sub>]] (like that of PF<sub>5</sub>) consists of single resonance near room temperature.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Walter G. |last1=Klemperer |first2=Jeanne K. |last2=Krieger |first3=Michael D. |last3=McCreary |first4=E. L. |last4=Muetterties |first5=Daniel D. |last5=Traficante |first6=George M. |last6=Whitesides |title=Dynamic nuclear magnetic resonance study of fluorine exchange in liquid sulfur tetrafluoride |journal=J. Am. Chem. Soc. |date=1975 |volume=97 |page=7023–7030 |DOI=10.1021/ja00857a012}}</ref> The four atoms in motion act as a lever about the central atom; for example, the four fluorine atoms of sulfur tetrafluoride rotate around the sulfur atom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch.ic.ac.uk/rzepa/bpr/ |title=Illustration of the Berry pseudorotation}}</ref>
==Examples== [[Sulfur tetrafluoride]] is the premier example of a molecule with the disphenoidal molecular geometry (see image at upper right). The following compounds and ions have disphenoidal geometry:<ref>[http://www.chemthes.com/entity_datapage.php?id=3087 Seesaw Molecular Geometry, AX4E1] 25 Dec 2007 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103162927/http://www.chemthes.com/entity_datapage.php?id=3087 |date=November 3, 2014 }}</ref>
*[[Sulfur tetrafluoride|SF<sub>4</sub>]] *[[Selenium tetrafluoride|SeF<sub>4</sub>]] *{{chem|IF|2|O|2|−}} *IOF<sub>3</sub> *{{chem|ClF|4|+}} *[[Tellurium tetrafluoride|TeF<sub>4</sub>]] *XeO<sub>2</sub>F<sub>2</sub> *{{chem|AsF|4|−}}
